## Code Quality

- **Self-documenting code** - Write code that explains itself through clear naming
- **Small functions** - Keep functions focused on a single task
- **DRY principle** - Extract repeated code into reusable functions/components
- **SOLID principles** - Follow Single Responsibility, Open/Closed, and Dependency Inversion

## Naming Conventions

- **Descriptive names** - Use clear, descriptive names that reveal intent
- **Avoid abbreviations** - Write full words except for common abbreviations (e.g., `id`, `api`, `url`)
- **Boolean naming** - Prefix booleans with `is`, `has`, `should` (e.g., `isValid`, `hasError`)
- **Plural for collections** - Use plural names for arrays/lists (e.g., `users`, `endpoints`)

## Error Prevention

- **Fail fast** - Validate inputs early and return errors immediately
- **Type safety** - Leverage type systems to prevent errors at compile time
- **Null safety** - Use `Option`/`Optional` or null checks to handle missing values
- **Explicit over implicit** - Make behavior explicit rather than relying on defaults

## Security

- **No secrets in code** - Never commit passwords, API keys, or tokens
- **Hash passwords** - Always hash passwords before storage (using password4j in backend)
- **Validate all inputs** - Validate and sanitize all user inputs
- **Lowercase for uniqueness** - Store emails and logins in lowercase for case-insensitive comparison

## Performance

- **Lazy loading** - Load resources only when needed
- **Database indexes** - Ensure frequently queried fields are indexed
- **Connection pooling** - Use connection pools for database access (HikariCP)
- **Caching** - Cache expensive computations and API calls when appropriate

## Documentation

- **README for setup** - Document setup and running instructions
- **API documentation** - Generate OpenAPI/Swagger docs for HTTP APIs
- **Inline docs for complexity** - Document complex algorithms and business rules
- **Keep docs up to date** - Update documentation when code changes
